Unsupervised Learning Project: AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on Unsupervised Learning. We will be using Credit Card Customer Data for this project.

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers.

Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers' queries are resolved faster. The head of marketing and the head of delivery, both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

Identify different segments in the existing customer base, taking into account their spending patterns as well as past interactions with the bank.

About the data¶

Data is available on customers of the bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which the customer has contacted the bank for any queries. These different channels include visiting the bank, online, and through a call center.

  • Sl_no - Customer Serial Number
  • Customer Key - Customer identification
  • Avg_Credit_Limit - Average credit limit (currency is not specified, you can make an assumption around this)
  • Total_Credit_Cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total_visits_bank - Total bank visits
  • Total_visits_online - Total online visits
  • Total_calls_made - Total calls made

n = data.shape[1]

# Save components to a DataFrame
data_pca = pd.DataFrame(principal_components, columns = data.columns)

# Creating copy of the data to store labels from each algorithm

data_copy = data_pca.copy(deep = True)

K-Means¶

Let us now fit the K-means algorithm on our pca components and find out the optimum number of clusters to use.

We will do this in 3 steps:

  1. Initialize a dictionary to store the Sum of Squared Error (SSE) for each K
  2. Run for a range of Ks and store SSE for each run
  3. Plot the SSE vs K and plot the elbow curve
In [18]:
# step 1
sse = {} 

# step 2 - iterate for a range of Ks and fit the pca components to the algorithm. 
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, max_iter = 1000, random_state = 1).fit(data_pca)
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_     # Use inertia attribute from the clustering object and store the inertia value for that K

# step 3
plt.figure()

plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")

plt.ylabel("SSE")

plt.show()

Question 4:¶

  • Interpret the above elbow plot and state the reason for choosing K=3 (1 Mark)
  • Fit the K-means algorithms on the pca components with the number of clusters equal to 3 (2 Mark)
  • Store the predictions as 'Labels' to the 'data_copy' and 'data' DataFrames (2 Marks)

The Sum of Squared Errors is decreasing sharply until K = 3 and then significantly less sharply afterwards. This means that further increasing the numbers of clusters past will not necessarily explain the data more, but computational costs will increase, thus we pick K = 3 to make sure clusters still capture the differences in the data without being too detailed.

In [19]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 3, random_state = 1)                      # Apply the K-Means algorithm

kmeans.fit(data_pca)                                                # Fit the kmeans function on the pca components

# Adding predicted labels to the original data and the copied data 
data_copy['Labels'] = kmeans.predict(data_pca)     # Save the predictions on the pca components from K-Means
data['Labels'] = kmeans.predict(data_pca)             # Save the predictions on the pca components from K-Means

Cluster Profiles:

  • Cluster 2 has the least amount of individuals at only 49. They also have high average credit limits and total number of credit cards. This group consists of wealthier individuals who contact the bank more online than any other method, perhaps due to higher standard of living/access to technology. Their mean and median average credit limit is much higher than either of the other two groups, meaning that they are the small percentage outliers who have extreme wealth.
  • Cluster 1 is the largest group, they have a reasonable average credit limit as well as total number of cards. This is representative of the middle class or average credit user. They visit the bank more than any other class.
  • Cluster 0 is smaller than Cluster 2 but still sizeable. They have few credit cards and low credit limits. These are new borrowers and low-income individuals. They call more than any other class, likely due to limited access to transportation and technology. This cluster includes both new borrowers and low-income individuals due to its size. If it was more similar in size to the extreme upper end, it would just be low-income, but since new borrowers have to start somewhere, they fall into the lower end, bloating its size and giving the data a right skew rather than a normal distribution.
  • The PCA oriented booxplot graphs show that due to each of the cluster profiles picking a different method of communication, they all have a neutral impact on the analysis and minimal explanation on the variance of each group.

Comparing Clusters:

  • Group 0 is fairly similar between the two methods. They represent the same relative set of customers who are fairly similar to each other
  • Group 1 and 2 flipped between the two. This means that group 2 on K-Medoids is more similar to group 1 on K-means than it is to group 2 on K-means.
  • This is where the similarities more or less end. K-Medoids seems to have moved more of the outliers determined in the K-means algorithm into its group 1. This increases group 1's size to be more equal to the other groups, but doesn't necessarily represent the data better. K-Medoids seems a bit less "affected" by the outliers, but considering we are creating groupings, if there is a grouping of outliers that fits a certain customer type, this isn't optimal.

K-Means seems to represent the data groupings best. The 49 individuals with extremely high credit limits could be looked at for upselling as they are likely high spenders as well, however due to the fact that they have lots of cards already they likely shouldn't be offered new cards as that could increase stress. On the reverse side, the cluster of people with low amounts of cards could be offered more cards to help alleviate potential finance concerns.
